node.text:
@calemakar_ is off to a fantastic start, picking up where he left off last year with full confidence from the point making smart plays.

Remember last year we talked about being last man back at the point can actually be an advantage as you fake the shots and get defenders over omitting. Makar is crazy deceptive as his body language suggests the move he’s faking and he ensures to put himself in a position to motor out of the move. 

Gotta love a defender who can walk the line, enter the zone and get it down down low for your team with possession and finding seams. 

Looking forward to many more years of this. 

(Video compiled by: @dimfilipovic ).

Pettersson emerged into the league with a lot of question marks. Making dazzling moves in Sweden on the regular, many questioned whether or not hed be able to pull off these moves in the NHL.

Short answer: Yes.

Petterson is very aware of where he is, his teammates/opponents are, and where his advantages lie. As he approaches he sees the space he wants to get to, and reaches deep into his bag of tricks to pull off some incredible moves. Choosing the right move to match the unique situation he's in. 

Much like Datsyuk, so much of his dangles rely on body language fakes more than actually making stickhandles. This is especially dangerous when he has an odd man advantage as hes able to sell the pass to get the defender overcommitting before going the other way.

Video compiled by @dimfilipovic. Follow him on Twitter for more incredible videos like this one!

Brayden Point has been turning heads all post season, but he’s been doing it all year.  He has masterful puck protection skills that supplement his speed and edge work very well.

One thing you’ll notice Point does a lot is reposition his body to maximize leverage while protecting the puck. Whether that’s going one hand on the stick or maintaining that two handed position, he makes it very difficult for defenders to gain access to the puck.

And what happens if they go for the puck? That gives Point a slight advantage which with his speed and edge work proves to be quite the advantage for him to create gaps. 

Like Crosby, he absorbs contact well while protecting the puck, and he is always aiming to maintain as much speed as he can throughout the sequence!  Big time player for TB  as he allows his team to maintain possession more, but he’s also very fierce and tactical in 50/50 play, allowing his team to get the puck more and gaining better scoring opportunities.

Always remember to look at the little details. It’s skills like this that mean more time to setup and make plays for your team. These little battles are usually where games are won and lost. 

Credit to @dimfilipovic for the video. If you don’t follow him on Twitter already I HIGHLY advise you do. Great eye for skill if you like vids like this.

node.text:
Lafrieniere has been torching the Q with @oceanicrimouski.

In his 3rd season with the club he has recorded 112pts in just 52 games. He also had a terrific showimg for Canadas World Junior squad with 4 goals 6 assists 10pts in 5GP.

He controls the pace incredibly well and has great vision. 77 of those 112 points were assists and 35 were goals. He can certainly finish but he's also a great puck distributer.

He can rip the puck with good velocity and a quick release that often shocks goaliez, and his accuracy is very lethal.

And then his ability to see the ice and find the higher probability play immediately is what is setting him apart from other players significantly. The best since Crosby to play for Rimouski and there are stunning similarities in their game.

Can't wait to see this kid buzzing in the league. (Video Source: @nhl).

Sidney Crosby has undeniably good vision, and his ability to distribute the puck serves to compliment that quite well. He’s constantly seeing the game 1-2 steps ahead and he is so good at finding the players tape.

Whether it’s a backhand small area sauce, a bank off the boards, or just a good crisp forehand pass, Crosby has made other players around him better for over a decade by finding them and giving them ideal shooting position or make another play.

Crosby has 801 assists in 984 GP. When you have a player who is so strong in 50/50 corner battles and puck protection...and passing it’s a pretty dangerous combination. His wingers love him. 
Another spectacular video from xxlaflammexx who individually seeks out skill separators from Crosby in a compilation. The time and effort he puts into it is incredible please support his YouTube channel if you love this content. Full videos are there too.

node.text:
In past videos we’ve showcased Crosby’s elite playmaking, backhander, puck protection, skating, edges and quick release.

This video aims to take a closer look at dropping to the one knee to gain leverage.

By dropping to the one knee you able to get more strength on the stick which can be lethal from certain positions on the ice and for harder passes where we need the blade to be stronger . It also allows you to get under the puck easier, allowing you to go top shelf far easier from tighter circumstances.

Crosby is a mastermind of hockey. That can never be disputed. And we’ve talked about his straight curve before and how that allows him to have a better backhand, as well as redirect the puck well on both sides of the blade. Straighter curve patterns are harder to elevate the puck and Crosby is well aware of that and has made the necessary adjustments in his shot. And this knee drop shot is one great example of how he adapts to the situation well. He’s worked endlessly on it and can do this consistently. You’ll rarely find a puck go through the blade of Crosby as he’s always ensuring he has the right positioning and strength to control and release it.
